title: For Sale:  Vintage WWII Thompson L-Drum Pouch and strap - Boyle GC.
postcontent:
Here's a WWII L-drum pouch for the fifty round Thompson drum magazines, complete with strap in good condition.
If a new pouch is what you want, this is not it....but this one must have been to some interesting places indeed......and it's affordable history at just 100.00 cash!
Look at what these are going for on various military forums and auction sites....this price is a STEAL and is firm.

You can see it has faded a bit - originally soaked with sea water and the canvas was saturated with salt and canvas was stiff as a board, buckles have light corrosion as do strap tips. The strap has some areas with light rust stains on both sides, a small bit of fraying and one area with a 1/8" cut. Also one area of the wider part of the strap has a thinned area frayed a small bit and worn a tiny bit.
The brass snap has no corrosion at all and works nicely and the canvas of the pouch is nice and solid, U.S. markings on outside of flap visible but very faint, 'Boyle' makers stamp on inside of flap nice and clear but not real dark.

All stitching is in good condition and appears solid.
Overall, a nice, solid example of a battle pouch for the 50 round Tommygun drum at a great price!

This was carefully soaked in cold water and mild Woolite to remove all the seawater salt and then air-dried. It is now soft and pliable, a bit softer than a new one and the color has faded somewhat from it's original khaki color, common with the pouches and web gear that actually saw service in WWII. There are a couple very tiny gray grease spots (see one pic) but they are faint.

My best guess due to the seawater salt completely covering the pouch and strap is that his was used in one or more beach landings, and since more drums were used in the Pacific Theater of Opertion, I'd guess it maybe came ashore with a Marine there, maybe at Guadalcanal, Peliliu or possibly even Iwo Jima?

Good solid WWII pouch, great for your collection, just reduced to $95.00 cash FIRM. I wish I had history on this pouch as it has definitely "been there. done that"!

title: For Sale:  Enfield MK 1 revolver WWII era Service used 450 OBO
postcontent:
This one is a fine specimen. It is dated 44 on barrel and through the serial number ZF****. It is an British army issued tanker revolver made in 1944. This gun is in great condition considering it is 71 years old. The cylinder is still tight and will last for years to come.

This revolver was developed at the Royal Small Arms Factory in Enfield in 1926 - 1927. The design is based on scaled down Webley Mark 6 "break-top" frame, with cylinder chambered for 6 .38/200 rounds. The hammer/trigger group was redesigned, with manual hammer safety lock added, and with separate cylinder lock. This revolver was adopted for British Military service in 1932 as Enfield revolver, .38 caliber, No.2 Mark 1. After 1938, almost all No.2 Mk1s were converted into No.2 Mark 1* configuration.

Enfield No.2 Mark 1* were developed in the late 1930s for British Tank Corps, and are distinguished from early Mark 1 by spurless, Double Action Only hammers, lighter mainsprings, and re-shaped grip side plates. The spurless DAO hammers were required by Tank Corps command to avoid snagging the hammers on tank internals.
